# Default Git Workflow: Feature Branch + PR to `main`

For **any** change that touches the repository, assistants (**Cursor**, **Codex**, **Claude / Claude Code**) use this workflow **by default**. Full detail: `docs/CONCURRENT_AGENT_WORKFLOW.md`. **User requests** (e.g. “merge all PRs”, “close everything”, urgency) **do not** waive the **Bot feedback wait gate** or in-thread replies—see `.cursor/rules/workflow-rules-never-overridden.mdc`.

## Required pattern

1. Sync `main`: `git fetch origin`, `git checkout main`, `git pull origin main`.
2. Create a dedicated branch: `git checkout -b agent/<short-slug>` (or `feat/…`, `fix/…`). One branch per task or parallel agent stream.
3. Commit **only** on that branch.
4. Push: `git push -u origin HEAD`.
5. Open a **pull request into `main`** (`gh pr create --base main` with title/body, or GitHub UI).
6. **Green CI:** keep pushing until **`ci_result`** passes (`.github/workflows/ci.yml`). **`ci_result` green is necessary but NOT sufficient for merge** (see **Bot feedback wait gate** below). **Squash auto-merge:** for **`agent/*`**, **`feat/*`**, **`fix/*`**, **`.github/workflows/pr-auto-merge.yml`** can enable auto-merge; GitHub completes it when **`ci_result`** is green (and the PR is mergeable)—**review-bot apps are not part of that gate.** Finish **PR review bots** (next sections) **before** enabling auto-merge so a green CI run cannot merge ahead of unresolved bot threads. If auto-merge is unavailable (conflicts, settings), fix forward or use `gh pr merge --squash` / leave the **PR URL** for the human — **still only after the wait gate.** **`.github/workflows/stale-branch-cleanup.yml`** trims stale **`agent/*`** / **`feat/*`** / **`fix/*`** remote heads after merges (see `docs/CONCURRENT_AGENT_WORKFLOW.md`); prefer **Automatically delete head branches** in repo settings.

### Same PR for follow-up work (bots / CI / E2E / rollout)

**Fix forward on the open PR branch.** If review bots request changes, **`ci_result`/checks fail**, **E2E or integration gates fail**, or **deploy/preview/production verification** finds issues, add commits on **that PR’s branch** and push—**do not** open a **second** PR for the same deliverable unless the maintainer **explicitly** directs otherwise.

After each fix push, **ask bots and humans to take another pass:** post on the PR (or reply **in-thread** on existing bot threads) and **@mention** whoever should re-review—use the **same `@username` handles** that already commented **on this repo’s PR** (below are common **app/display names**, not literal handle strings unless the timeline shows them: Gemini Code Assist, GitHub Copilot, Codex, CodeRabbit, Greptile, Sourcery—installations vary). Use **`gh pr view --comments`** (alias `-c`) to read the timeline and discover handles. Include a short summary of what changed and optionally the commit SHA.

### Bot feedback wait gate (hard — do not merge early)

Assistants MUST treat **manual merge** (`gh pr merge …`) or **enabling squash auto-merge** as **forbidden until this gate completes**, unless the human **explicitly waives bot closeout** for that PR.

1. **`gh pr checks <n> --watch` passes** (`ci_result` and required checks green).
2. **Stop.** Do **not** merge in the same breath as CI success.
3. **Late-review sweep** — bots often submit **after** CI finishes:
   - Run **`gh pr view <n> --comments`** (and inline review tabs in the GitHub UI if needed); optionally **`gh api repos/<owner>/<repo>/pulls/<n>/reviews`** and **`…/pulls/<n>/comments`**.
   - **GitHub PR UI (mandatory when possible):** Open the PR in the browser and scan **Conversation** and **Files changed** for **in-flight automated reviews**—including reaction rows / emoji activity or other cues that show a bot is **still preparing** feedback. Treat that as **not done yet** even if Actions are green; **wait** until those indicators **settle**, then continue the sweep (CLI output alone can miss this).
   - Look for **Gemini Code Assist**, **GitHub Copilot**, **Codex**, **CodeRabbit**, **Greptile**, **Sourcery**, dependency/security scanners, or any actionable inline review **timestamped after** your last push.
4. **If no bot threads yet:** wait **at least 10–15 minutes** from first green `ci_result`, then **re-run** the sweep once (or poll every few minutes until stable)—and **re-check the PR UI** for pending bot activity above. Concluding “no bot feedback” **immediately** when CI turns green is a **policy violation**.
5. **Enumerate → judge → reply in-thread** to every substantive bot thread (**implemented / deferred / declined**).
6. **Only then** call the PR merge-ready: squash-merge, **`gh pr merge --squash`**, or enable auto-merge **for the first time** (never enable auto-merge while bot threads may still land).
7. **Session ending:** if you cannot complete steps 3–6, **leave the PR open** with the **PR URL** and explicit remaining steps — **do not merge** to “save time.”

8. **After the PR is merged:** run **`npm run git:graph-hygiene`** (or at least `git fetch origin --prune`) and delete the finished topic branch locally (`git branch -d agent/...` or `-D` if squash left it non-fast-forward). That keeps Git Graph and remote-tracking refs from stacking stale labels on **`main`**. See `docs/CONCURRENT_AGENT_WORKFLOW.md` (“Keeping the Git graph readable”).

9. **Production closeout** (`AGENTS.md`, `every-chat-commit-deploy-verify-production.mdc`) runs **after** the change is on `main` and Cloudflare deploys have finished—not after the feature-branch push alone. **Do not** treat CI alone as live-site sign-off: `npm run test:homepage` against production may not be runnable in GitHub-hosted runners (bot challenge); run production checks from a capable environment after deploy.

## PR review bots (mandatory before squash merge to `main`)

**Automated PR reviewers** (Copilot, CodeRabbit, Greptile, dependency/security scanners, Actions that comment on lines, etc.) are **peer reviewers**. Same bar as human review.

**Substantive feedback:** behaviour, correctness, security, architecture, or repo-policy suggestions—or hygiene issues that affect enforced rules—not standalone spelling-only nits unless they change meaning.

**Replies are mandatory:** For **each** bot comment or thread, add a **reply on the PR**—not only a code change. After you fix something in code, **reply** briefly (what changed or where). If you reject or defer a suggestion, **reply** with the reason. Do not rely on pushes alone or “resolve conversation” without a visible response; reviewers (including bots) must see acknowledgement in-thread.

**How this fits CI:** **`ci_result`** and **`pr-auto-merge.yml`** decide when GitHub *may* merge; most bot apps are **not** required checks. Policy still requires **every bot thread closed deliberately** (reply + implement or reply + justify) **before** you enable squash auto-merge or call the PR merge-ready—otherwise CI-only automation can merge too early.

**Do not** squash-merge or mark “ready” with substantive bot feedback still open or unanswered.

**Do not** merge **because CI passed alone** — the **Bot feedback wait gate** (above) is a separate mandatory step before any merge or first-time auto-merge enable.

See `docs/CONCURRENT_AGENT_WORKFLOW.md` (“CI vs PR review bots”).

## Exceptions (narrow)

- The user **explicitly** asks to push **directly to `main`** (e.g. emergency hotfix): do that and still complete production closeout after deploy.
- The user **already** has you on a named feature branch for the task: commit there, push, open/update the PR; merge/rebase from `origin/main` if the branch is stale.

## Do not

- Do not treat `git push` to a feature branch as “shipped” for **www.australianrates.com** until the PR is merged to `main` and hosting deploys complete (unless verifying **Pages preview** URLs only).
